76561198034379048,Recommended,248610,28880539,"Posted: 31 December, 2016",all,Soxxox Smox,"Fans of Frozen Synapse, Breach and Clear, and other similar tactical games will love Doorkickers, and with good reason - it has a lot to offer, whether you're a meticulous perfectionist or you prefer to run your plans fast and loose. Since you can pause the game to revise your plan (or even alter it in real-time) at any point, it's entirely up to you how active you want to be in guiding your soldiers through each level. You can even try to run a mission with a single trooper. Outside of missions, you can spend the stars you've earned to unlock new equipment for your troopers, and experience will unlock small skill improvements. All the elements of the game come together fairly well - the differences in classes and weapons are small enough that players who aren't concerned with meticulously min-maxing their loadouts can ignore them, but still significant enough to allow for lots of tactical options. The simple controls mean you can create plans and revise plans very quickly and easily.Doorkickers does have a few issues, particularly with the control scheme. It's sometimes difficult to predict what a particular trooper will do in a particular situation, particularly if you're the kind of player who likes to plan the whole mission out ahead of time. For example, if you order a trooper to breach a room with a flashbang, and that door is already open when he arrives at it, he will head in without throwing one, sometimes leading to his death. Multi-story buildings don't allow you to create plans past the first story. Missions with lots of troopers will clutter up the screen with countless paths and orders.Perhaps most frustrating to me, as someone who is used to Frozen Synapse's determinism, is the element of randomness in every engagement. Sometimes the difference between a good plan resulting in success or total failure is up to random enemy unit placements and split-second chances, meaning that to get that perfect 3 star score, you sometimes just have to keep running the mission until the stars align and everything goes right.But I think it says something about how much fun Doorkickers is that despite these annoyances, I'm still heavily recommending it. I've had a lot of fun with it so far and it's great for a quick fix of tactical gameplay. As I'm writing this, it's on sale for 2.99 which is a fantastic deal.Oh the soundtrack is nice too."
