,Recommended,248610,20206921,"Posted: 1 January, 2016",all,Obawan,"A lot of people compare Door Kickers to Breach & Clear, and even The Masterplan. Where this is probably a good comparison in terms of genre and what to expect, Door Kickers is far more fluid and boasts a rather active community giving the game experience a slight edge over Breach & Clear and perhaps a lasting experience.The concept is pretty simple. You run a SWAT-like squad which you are able to level up through single missions (""training"") and get to equip them with weapon and armour upgrades as you complete missions, level up your squad and gain ""roster stars"". These you spend on upgrades. You can also gain a type of skill point that you can use to improve the 3 basic weapon trees: hand-guns, assault, shot-guns. These all become bigger, brighter and better as you progress and start to unlock other roles for your squad: breacher, assaulter, stealth and a shielder.The workshop community have already created a large array of mission rooms and campaigns, but there is also an editor in-game and random room creator that help to gain those level ups before tackling the storyline campaigns.This isn't your Real World SWAT team. Don't expect negotiation abilities, or actual SWAT tactics to retrieve hostages. The game borrows from SWAT. Once you can accept that, then the game is pretty fun. You can stop/pause to plot within the mission or campaign, or run it fluidly which I think really adds to the atmosphere of the game. Fog of War obscures rooms and areas, so trying to clear out a biker gang hideout, or safely escort a VIP from a train station can be daunting, exciting and full of action if you don't pick the right squad members or plot your actions carefully.Leave no door unopened. Even if it is a toilet. Tangos hide in toilets.Overall, if you want something harking back to the old SWAT games, you may not like Door Kickers not keeping to SWAT regulations and realism. Otherwise, if you like using spy cameras to check out rooms for the bad guys, breaching with a shot gun, or using a shield guy as a decoy whilst you flank from behind some cars in a parking garage, you will probably really enjoy Door Kickers."
