76561197980299044,Not Recommended,248610,13454944,"Posted: 19 December, 2014",all,!_UnSeEn_!,"NOTE: This review was last updated on 19 Dec, 2014 @ 4:49pm. Things I talked about may now be irrelevant. I will update this review in the near future as I have stopped progressively playing Doorkickers.As much as want to enjoy Door Kickers, as I am a big fan of Tactic RTS's , this one has given me the most frustation yet, and not in a good, challenging way either. Although my hours spent on this game at the time of this review is few, the movement mechanics have already hindered a positive impression from me. Often times, the fault in my plans is not in my ability, but in the broken mechanics of the game.When things work out and bugs such as shooting at the wall because the target is to my characters adjacent isn't a problem, the game is fun. Watching my team swiftly move in and clearing the area under a designated time feel rewarding and I can see what the dev's envision. But, having a constant struggle with things like redoing my carefully laid out plan because adding a step would somehow erase the previous ones, or, being unable to peak around the corner of a doorway because the action menu of breaching methods block my cursor from selecting my move node, breaks the experience for me.Among all my concerns however, the two big annoyances are when my team disregards the assigned command call (ex. Alpha, Bravo), and moves in on their own, and, when the units move before clearing a newly breached room. The work around for for the first issue is to redo my whole plan which, as mentioned before, is a chore that takes away from the fun.Although my review has mostly been negative, this is not a bad game at all. In fact, I would recommend you to give it as try as this review is soley based on my own critique. You may overlook these minor flaws and thoroughly enjoy this game. But for me, these minor issues were little details that became a major hassle as I played on."
76561198005971335,Not Recommended,248610,31885818,Posted: 21 May,all,Axelrad,"If you want a realistic tactics game in the vein of a top-down Rainbow Six or SWAT 4, as many people seem to compare this to, I'd pass and get Frozen Synapse instead - it lacks the realistic veneer, but has much more meat to it. And even though Door Kickers has the appearance of realism, it's actually a grindy mobile-style game that I found to be a casual diversion more than anything, only worth the time if you can get it cheap. Not only was it disappointing, but I surprisingly found Breach & Clear to be the more entertaining ""casual tactics"" game.There's a lot of nice stuff here that makes it look like a top-down SWAT 5 at first glance - go codes (a huge deal!), micromanagement of inventory & team assignments, permadeath campaigns, a veneer of realism. But it's all ultimately let down by a massive heap of grind, a lack of authenticity, and a complete and utter lack of any story/narrative element.The grind is the biggest and most pervasive problem. The game starts you out with only the absolute barebones of classes and gear available, and everything else is locked behind time-gates, requiring you to dump hours of play into the game before you even have all the basic classes available and can start to think about preparing complicated entry strategies. At first I approvingly thought this was just a tutorial bit, easing the player into the game one class at a time, but Door Kickers just keeps doing it, making you really grind to get all the classes. Eventually the levels become gated by unrealistically overpowered enemies, requiring you to go back and grind up more until you have all the best weapons and armors and whatnot. Your officers also gain XP the more you use them, so just grinding up the same team in the same mission over and over and over makes them way more effective in combat. When you consider roster space, you basically have to do this twice in order to have a fully-leveled roster, and from what I've seen from other players, this is pretty much required for the ""end-game"" campaigns if you want your your officers to compete with the enemy AI in anything (I certainly didn't stick with the game long enough to get that far.)My other two points are very connected. Even though Door Kickers is presented as and often hailed as an ""authentic"" tactics game, it's basically just a casual puzzle game with SWAT graphics, more akin to Angry Birds than SWAT 2. This doesn't make it a bad game per say, but it just doesn't hold water when compared to games that present actual tactical problems and solutions. Enemies and missions are far from authentic, and even though you're supposed to be playing a SWAT team, every mission boils down to a terrorist hunt challenge. Every enemy is always killed, no situation is ever complicated, and the only arrests are quick scripted events during certain mission types. Compared to something like the SWAT series, which allowed for a wide range of interactions and mission types *over a decade* ago, Door Kickers seems quite limited. The only innovative thing about it is the neat field of view thing they borrowed from stealth games, but this ultimately cannot carry a game.Then there's the lack of story. If the mechanics are amazing I could forgive this, but they're not. And there's absolutely NO story or narrative element anywhere in the game - not even the little pre-mission briefings that have always been the norm for this type of game. Every level is challenge mode scenario. Your only incentive is a high score. Just challenge scenario after challenge scenario, which eventually becomes repetative. It all might as well be hologram training. There *is* a campaign mode, but all it is is a series of linked scenarios that feature permadeath & injury memory carrying over between them, thus making them more interesting and challenging. Absolutely nothing in the way of any additional narrative connection or setup. Instead every single scenario is a simple terrorist hunt or some basic objective that often boils down to being a terrorist hunt anyway."
