,Recommended,248610,14552796,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,sjcbcolby,"Door kickers is a fantastic top down shooter, but not quite like every other one.What sets door kickers apart is its almost 'blueprint' type of plan and play. The base of the game is you have a squad of customizable soldiers that you must guide through a small area in a strategic way while taking as few casualties as possible and comleting the objective. The objectives range from anything from saving hostages, to disarming bombs, to simply killing every enemy and more.How to command each soldier is relatively simple, click and drag a path for them to follow. If you want to get fancy you can even right click and drag an arrow to where you want them to look at different points on the path making for effective straffing manuvers. You must plan your path carefully because you are not given the location of your enemies and therefore it pays to be strategic. If you do futz it up, there is a pause button that you can activate anytime durring the mission and replan your squads next move.Obtaining new equipment for your soldiers is like other games with a progression system. as you progress you get points to spend on new equipment such as heavier bullet-proof vests, new weapons, riot shields, etc.Although the customization may make the game seem unfair and favor you, it counters that by giving you a ton of enemies or the satisfaction of knowing that you planned just right. For example, if there's a room of 10 enemy soldiers right in front of you and you only have 4 guys, you're not going to send them all in with ligh armour and tiny pistols. What you can do is customize your squad to have heavy armour, have 2 swap out their primary weapons for riot shields, and the others to carry assault riffles and stack up on each other providing heavy fire and protection in the trade off for mobility and a quick trigger finger. It's these trade offs that make the difference in how you plan and make the strategic aspect of the game very inportant.There is also a skill tree menu for your soldiers. Along with unlocking new equipment you can 'train' your team to give them boosts such as aiming faster, more accurately, following up with a second shot to make sure the enemy is dead, hold their fire for those who like to be stealthy, and so on and so forth.The game also has a number of little things it will throw in from time to time to help it feel a little more 'real'. This includes an uncertain amount of baddies on many levels, 'cause who knows if they called for back up of not? You occasionally get a sniper friend to help you because back up never hurt you either (in fact, it seems a little overpowered, but I'm not complaining). Your soldiers CAN die! After all those missions you go through together, all the promotions they've earned, all the gear you've given them, and they just one day *pew pew* and you just have to sit there for a minute wondering why you were so foolish and sent your commerade out into a blaze of fire and know you lost the best soldier on your team *sniffle sniffle*. (Quietly whispers) ""He was so young..."" Ok, now back to what I was saying. You must also tell your crew to reload because contrary to many games, you don't just majically know when to reload, you first have to walk into enemy fire, pull the trigger, realize you're out of ammo, and get shot in the midst of reloading because you forgot to tell your poor soldier to reload. This isn't to forget that there is a cover system in the game. If you can pull out and behind a barrel to give yourself adequate cover for a moment, it could really save you in a pinch, and if you're like me, give an oppertunity to reload. Before I get too far off topic I should mention that you do gain new soldiers back ofter a few missions, they may grow on trees in this game, but that doesn't mean it's an instant replacement.Door Kickers also assists you by adding stealth mechanics also (but let's be honest, guns aren't the quietest things).The line of sight really is your best friend in this game because as long as you can intrude it by hiding behind a door or something (Are you happy now? I mentioned doors just like you were waiting for), you can use this to help get into a good spot to take down the enemy from all sides, or over all to your advantage depending on the plan. In adition to the line of sight, you should also try to be relatively quiet unless you bring out the big guns. This is thanks to a small sound system they threw in so you can't simply blow up doors and have ever enemy go ""Hey, you hear something?"" and the other guy say ""Nah, it's probably just the wind"" *cough* skyrim *cough*.Now although It's easy to slip up (like me) and forget to reload (like me) and get your people killed (like me), your not completely hopeless. The fix to being an idiot (guess like who? yup, like me) is to add a somewhat self sufficent AI, so if your soldier runs into a tough spot or gets shot by someone out of their line of sight, they can do things like turn to them and shoot them, or if they're heavily armoured and can take a few hits to buy some time before dying and their clip ran out, they will try to reload it. Although it may not seem like it, this small bit of AI that can help take care of little things can really help win a mission.Now, finally you say, ""Okay, I beat the game, what now?"" Well, the good people that made this game thought of that and have little side objectives such as complete a level without causualties ot in a certain time frame or something to help add some play time. When you finish with that there's even more. They even threw in a random map generator to add even more hours of play. You just have to put in what you want, things such as: nuber of enemies, map size, if you want fog of war, etc. and out pops a map for you. Pretty nice, huh?Given that the game is called Door Kickers, you may be reading this and say ""Hey, what's with the lack of busting down doors?"" and so this goes out to you. You can:-pick the lock-use a crowbar-C4-Blast if open with a shot gun-open it and chuck a grenade through-make a sound to lure the baddies and have them open it for you-whatever else you can think of doing, you got options, be creative and knock yourself out.Rating: 9/10Very solid experience in my time, try not to run directly into a house full of enemies and you should be pretty set. The progression system isn't a favorite of mine and the line of sight can be weird sometimes, but hey, it's not half bad."
