,Recommended,248610,20245252,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,The Salty Survivor,"Door Kickers is a game about commanding 2 to 8 armed officers, and fighting randomly generated terrorists through premade maps.This game's controls are simple and easy to understand, but can also provide the ability to execute advanced commands and the ability to co-ordinate your team.There are 5 classes to choose from, I have unlocked only 4 at the time of writing this review, and I can say that the shield has served me practically no use, although the other 3 classes (Pointman, Assaulter, Breacher) have proved most useful and indespensible aspects of a successful team.The way of customizing loadouts is using a currency called stars. You unlock these stars by completing missions and completing certain criteria, the criteria to earn a full three stars are to not lose a single unit and to score a time below the limit given. This must not be confused with a speedrun, as the game can be paused and tactics and actions can be prepared in the paused state, ready to be performed when the game is running again. 15 seconds ingame can become a whole minute if you pause a lot.However, if you spend your stars on bad weapons, or on one class alone, you may find yourself in a whole that you dug yourself into, and I thoroughly dislike the randomly generated terrorists, and I found my troops sometimes turning their back to danger despite my orders.(Edit 1) In the campaigns, which are a series of missions in which soldiers are perminently KIA for the duration of it if lost, I have found that soldiers that are killed are lost, and their stat gains from promotions are also lost. This adds a benefit to not just going ham and sending all of your men in to be slaughtered, which is always a plus for an RTS.But overall, I would recommend this game, I felt like quite a badass.And if you need an arbitrary rating, it gets my 8/10."
,Recommended,248610,20598536,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,Angularityッ,"Ignore the time Steam says I have played. I have played about 14 hours of the game overall, most of it done offline while I was traveling.Similar to: Hotline Miami, Rainbow Six 3, SWAT 4Pros-Simple controls that anyone can pick up.-Can be played with one hand.-Game mechanics may be simple, but allow for extremely complex strategies to be played out.-Versetile level editor.-Lots of content in the game, hundreds of standalone missions ranging in difficulty, as well as a handful of campaigns lasting 1 to 2 hours each.-Randomized mission generator.-Scenario Variety-Perfect game to play on a laptop if you have a mouse.-Officer and Squad progression. (new skills, weapons, and classes to unlock)-Pause and play allows you to assess the situation on an action by action basis, giving the player time to think and plan.-Good soundtrack.-Playing with your own music/podcast in the background takes nothing away from the game.Cons-Enviroments can get repetitive. (The level design is varried, I'm talking about the way they look)-Controls don't work well when trying to play in real time.-Some of the bigger levels can get tedious, especially if you are stuck looking for the last enemy, hostage, bomb, etc.-How fast your guys react to getting shot at is random at times.-Steath is underdeveloped.ConclusionThis is the most fun I have had in an RTS ever. This is coming from someone who doesn't really like RTS games. I decided to give this game a shot, mainly because I am a fan of squad based Tactical FPS's (Swat 4 and Arma 3 being my favorites) and this game shared the same concepts. Overall, the game is accessible, but still has the complexity to please seasoned RTS verterans.Recommended to: Players who are looking for an accessible game that has a challenging tactical experience that does not rely on clunky UI or twitch shooting.9 out of 10"
