76561198034545371,Recommended,248610,8001123,"Posted: 10 December, 2013",all,hssaints30,The first review was an Early alpha Review I am pleased to say after revisting the game it has improved vastly I actually enjoyed it.
,Recommended,248610,12652309,"Posted: 26 October, 2014",all,KennyRogersJackass,"Door Kickers: 6/10Door Kickers is an interesting concept -- one that's been done before, but not as often as people hope. The cult classic Rainbow Six 3: Raven Shield being the quintessential example of this type of game, Door Kickers takes a similar approach in trying to create an atmosphere of tactical tension, albeit with a bit of levity involved in the presentation. In recent years, we've also seen the well-made Breach & Clear released, which was an underappreciated game that took the Rainbow Six formula, made it purely top-down, and focused the action in on three-second pseudo-realtime moments.So, there is quite an audience for this type of game built in already -- many people love this type of tactical action for two reasons; as games, they provide a thrill unlike any other. This isn't Call of Duty, where rasberry jam will be smeared all over your character's face if you improperly clear a room: if you fail to properly check your corners, your character will die, and this creates a sheer tension towards entering and moving through buildings in any properly executed Tactical game. A second reason is more of a gritty tactical feel -- it's not really the thrill of playing a game, but the thrill of using real tactics, real equipment, and truly mastering these raids until you can defeat most levels on the first try. Rainbow Six leaned towards the latter. Breach & Clear aimed towards the former. Door Kickers gets stuck somewhere in the middle.As a game, Door Kickers has a very 'hotshot' atmosphere. The achievements, menu tips, and even the interface all make it out as a Call of Duty-esque experience that challenges you to play. The gameplay can either be taken very tactically and slowly,  or in a more brash realtime mode where squaddies will just follow your mouse as long as you hold and drag them around. Neither of these modes works perfectly. For example; as a game, the gameplay quickly falls apart when you realize just how rote and routine winning each level becomes. Going back to Breach & Clear, each level was interesting enough, but sweeping rooms was really only half the battle. Using your items and abilities intelligently was really what carried you forwards. In Door Kickers, using items effectively is useful, but nonessential. Setting up intelligent fire zones and sweeping a room carefully will let you beat every single level in the game with the basic Assault class.And speaking more towards classes, the RPG elements of Door Kickers are not as deep as those presented in other games. If you're going to put a character progression system into a game, it has to feel like your characters are progressing. Let me explain: XCom: Enemy Unknown is a perfect example. In the earliest parts of the game, your recruits are pathetic. They can't shoot, they can't hit anything, and they have no useful abilities. They'll get slaughtered. However, as you play more and more, you really begin to bond with them; you create little vignettes in your head of everything they've done as soldiers, and you see them come to life with powerful abilities and interesting weapons. You thrill at their victories, and gasp at their failures. In Breach & Clear, this also happens; you create a squad of soldiers and deploy them for the entire game, slowly levelling them to the point of creating a cohesive crack team of unique and varied soldiers. Door Kickers really just expediates this process to the point where it's completely pointless. I had a maximum-level squad within the first five hours of gameplay, and none of my squad members really stood out. The small stat increases they receive are fairly pointless, and it's really their loadout that affects things more than their actual skill. Furthermore, you can just swap all of them between classes at will, so there's no real reason to specialize anyone. You gain a lot of tactical freedom, but lose all of the characters and personality that could've been developed here.So, Door Kickers isn't really a perfect game -- it's not too challenging, nor is it really relatable. So, is it, at least, tactical? To a degree, I would say it is, but in a very frustrating way. As aforementioned, it works as a room clearing simulator. Entering a room is interesting and fun, and you begin to pick up some actual tactical acumen as you play through the game. But then, you begin to suddenly realize what a dearth of options there really are in the game. You, of course, have five classes.Pointman - which becomes entirely useless about twenty minutes into the game,Assault - Which is the only class you really need to win every map,Breacher - Which is a nice class to have, but becomes a short-ranged assault about three hours into the game,Shield - Which is slow moving, doesn't do much damage, and is incredibly situational, and finallyStealth - Which is very similar to Assault, but completely superfluous and is preferable in only a few tiny instances.Now, the thing you may have noticed is that all of these classes seem to just bleed into the Assault class towards the end; the shield is, perhaps, the only one that remains entirely unique, and it's so rarely useable that it becomes like a health potion in a roleplaying game. You look at it, sigh, and say to yourself, ""Maybe next time. I should save it."" Furthermore, the inventories on all of the classes are almost entirely identical. Taking a game like Rainbow Six into account, you could arm any individual soldier with eight categories of weapons, each of which had twenty weapons, and several ammunition subtypes -- and that's not even getting into the modification system. In this game, each class has about 16 weapons available, and no modification system to speak of. As far as items go, the game is at a loss as well; this is a game about breaching and clearing rooms, so where the hell are the doorjams? Where are the fragmentation grenades? Where are the smoke grenades? Heartbeat sensors? Instead, you have some very basic options in the form of:Flashbangs - The most useful item in the game.Stingers - Very situational, not recommended.Breaching Charges - Situational, but you need something to pad your inventory.Lockpicks - Situational.Hammer - SituationalSnakecam - Mandatory.And a few others. Out of all of these, the three most useful ones are automatically equipped on the characters at the start of the game, making it pretty basic to load your troops out.So, then you get into the tactical meat of the game, and you become inundanted in a complete nightmare of artificial stupidity. The game makes a point to challenge you to use one plan to clear the entire building from the start of the match -- this is standard. Rainbow Six 1-3 were based on this concept of planning, and the planning room in this game is a pretty close recreation of what those games had. The only issue comes with the AI; both friendly and hostile. Your own troops are, for the most part, somewhat intelligent, but have moments of immense stupidity that make you want to throw your keyboard across the room. Your men start approaching a door, 2x2 cover formation. The door opens -- they quickly blow away the mook with an AK on the other side, and..They completely freeze in place. Why? Because I had them set to lockpick that door that he just blew open. The soldiers can't understand that the door isn't there, so they just stand and patiently wait. This is all well and fine when you have four guys stacked up, but when one soldier tries to pick the lock and a guy with a pistol opens the door, that soldier will just freeze, completely nonresponsive for minutes on end as the enemy tries to blow through his heavy body armor with the equivalent of an airsoft gun.I'd type more, but I have to cut this short; the game is buggy, unfair, and pretty shallow, but it's the closest a game has gotten to the old Rainbow Six feel. If you like those games, get it. You won't regret it."
