,Recommended,248610,33278739,Posted: 5 July,all,BP[Irudium],Not Bad
,Recommended,248610,33394378,Posted: 8 July,all,Kantele,"Tactics fans of the older Rainbow Six and SWAT games will definitely want to play this game. Realistic damage with an overhead view makes for an addicting experience. This game is deceptively simplistic, but it has a pretty robust planning system. You can plan an entire map before a bullet is even fired, but there is an on the fly planning feature, which is sometimes necessary to use to adapt your original plan. You can choose which directions to face while moving, waiting until areas are cleared, things like that.I love the XP system for a squad; you gradually earn skill points to spend in different ability trees as your squad levels up. There are also weapons and equipment you can purchase using stars earned from completed missions. And there is A LOT of content here; dozens of single missions, several campaigns consisting of linked missions where operative injury or death will carry over, and don't forget about the Steam Workshop support full of custom missions. I downloaded the Rainbow Six mod that substituted all the old music, chatter, and sound effects from the older games.Rainbow Six fans who loved to plan will find an itch scratched, but there are definitely areas left to be desired. The main complaint I have with the game is the planning is sometimes buggy or not deep enough. There are no teams, so you'll have to plan waypoints for each operative; that can get tedious if you're on a mission with 8 deployed. Often, if I'm trying to plan on the fly, I'll pause and put a go-code down for my man. Sometimes, if I try to plan a waypoint past it, it'll delete the go code and my man will just waltz into a room and ignore the original order. Other times, even when the go code is on a door, my operative will still ignore it and go charging in. The lack of depth is also frustrating: the game bases flashbanging rooms off of doors, but the AI is not smart enough to adapt to flashbang a room if a door is now open, when on the original plan it was closed. This forces you to have to order the flashbang again, but from outside the room. You'll have to redo any waypoints after that as well. Also, there are a couple multi-level maps where you can't even plan out the entire thing, making time trials far more difficult.I love the game when stuff goes right, but I find things slightly infuriating when the things that are going wrong are because the planning system is flawed in some key areas. Still, I can't help but come back to the game, because I still enjoy it immensely. When things go bad because of a boneheaded AI decision, I can only just shake my head and restart, trying to figure out a way around the game's jenk.But god damn, when I pull off a great takedown, you bet your♥♥♥♥♥I'm saving that replay. 7/10."
,Recommended,248610,33433818,Posted: 10 July,all,Epic,"Door Kickers is quite a phenominal game. I got this game because I remember all those moment playing team fps shooters, and me saying to myself when we lost, ""dood if i had control of our teamates i could pull off pro strats and win"".Well, this game has certainly proved me wrong. There are angles, armor, caliber, range, shields, and many other things in this game that make it the best tactical game mustered up. Different points and strategies of entry make difficult choices; should you flash in and move in your teamates from the other side of the room? Or should you perhaps plant charges on both sides and let mayhem spray out across everyone inside? These are the kind of planning details that I like to see. It's your own squad, you have complete control over them, and its overall just a great game.Customization. Door Kickers once again proves itself to me. Different weapons for each of the five classes, many sidearms, grenades, breaching charges, support gear, armor, it's everything that you would want to have in a real life scenario. You can also change every individual squad member (10 of them) to the name you like, the callsign you want for them, and the image that you believe fits them most.I've never seen more strategy guides for a single game. This should be more popular, I'm not sure why nobody has it. If you want an outstanding strategy game that you can play around with tactics and think to yourself, ""im a fockin master moi8"", Door Kickers is a definite for you.Overall, 9.5/10A must-buy for any shooter fan out there."
